Create an assistant

Use opendetail core when calling from Node without Next.js helpers.

`import { createOpenDetail } from "opendetail";

const assistant = createOpenDetail();
`

Then:

`const result = await assistant.answer({
question: "How do I configure public_path?",
});
`

answer() returns text, model, sources, images, fallback. stream() adds a ReadableStream<Uint8Array>.

Convenience wrapper

FumadocsAssistant (import from opendetail-fumadocs/assistant) bundles:

AssistantSidebar (with connection for endpoint/persistence when you pass those props)renderNextSourceLink from opendetail-nextcreateFumadocsSourceTargetResolver(knownSourcePageUrls)

Pass the same props you would to AssistantSidebar, plus knownSourcePageUrls. Site navigation chrome stays in your app (for example the demo’s Sidebar in apps/web), not in this package.

`import { FumadocsAssistant } from "opendetail-fumadocs/assistant";

<FumadocsAssistant
knownSourcePageUrls={["/docs", "/docs/quickstart", "/docs/core", /* … */]}
navigation={<YourNav />}
/* …AssistantSidebar props (e.g. endpoint, persistence) */
/>;
`

Wiring without the wrapper

Collect the doc page URLs your site actually serves (same slugs as your MDX routes), then pass them as knownPageUrls:

`import { createFumadocsSourceTargetResolver } from "opendetail-fumadocs";

const resolveSourceTarget = createFumadocsSourceTargetResolver([
"/docs",
"/docs/quickstart",
"/docs/core",
// …
]);
`

Pair with renderNextSourceLink from opendetail-next so resolved targets render as next/link where appropriate.

Local URLs must match a known pathname (no hash required for the allowlist match; hashes are preserved on output). Unknown paths like /docs/old-page resolve to null so the UI does not invent links.

Route handler

The scaffolded route is a thin wrapper:

`import { createNextRoute } from "opendetail-next";

export const { POST, runtime } = createNextRoute();
`

Or wire the handler yourself:

`import { createNextRouteHandler } from "opendetail-next";

export const runtime = "nodejs";
export const POST = createNextRouteHandler();
`

Requirements

Node.js 18+Route on the Node.js runtime (not Edge) for the default adapterOPENAI_API_KEY set where the handler runs.opendetail/index.json present after build

createNextRouteHandler accepts the same options as createOpenDetail (CreateOpenDetailOptions) when you need custom cwd, indexPath, or client injection.

Basic usage

`import { useOpenDetail } from "opendetail-react";

const {
messages,
question,
setQuestion,
submit,
stop,
status,
} = useOpenDetail({
transport: { endpoint: "/api/opendetail" },
});`

Basic usage

`import { createOpenDetailClient } from "opendetail-react";

const client = createOpenDetailClient({
endpoint: "/api/opendetail",
});

await client.submit(
{ question: "How do I install this?" },
{
  onEvent(event) {
    console.log(event);
  },
  onStatusChange(status) {
    console.log(status);
  },
}
);`

Import order

Import the base system stylesheet first, then optionally a theme:

@import "opendetail-base.css";
/* then one of: */
@import "opendetail-midnight.css";
@import "opendetail-signal.css";

Root elements use data-od-system="opendetail" where the layout marks the design system for theming.

Midnight

Cooler dark palette. Semantic color tokens (background, foreground, accent) shift while structure stays the same.

@import "opendetail-base.css";
@import "opendetail-midnight.css";

Signal

Warmer accent and palette variant on the same base contract — layout and components unchanged.

@import "opendetail-base.css";
@import "opendetail-signal.css";

Custom themes

Override semantic CSS variables scoped to data-od-system="opendetail" without forking React primitives. Place your overrides after the base import:

@import "opendetail-base.css";

[data-od-system="opendetail"] {
  --od-background: #0a0a0a;
  --od-accent: #6ee7b7;
}

Package paths follow your bundler's resolution for opendetail-react styles. See the style README for the full token list.
